<DOC><DOCNO> AP880328-0164 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 1924EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-28 0485</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0497</SECOND><HEAD>Cold Front Leaves Folks Shivering, Where They Were Basking OnSunday</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A cold front raced across the Rockies and Plains states Monday,bringing cold and snow to an area that had basked in springlikeweather over the weekend. A blizzard hit parts of Montana.   The temperature early Monday afternoon plunged to 33 degrees inPueblo, Colo., where a day earlier it had reached 85 degrees.Similar bone-chilling drops were reported across a wide region.   A blizzard raged across parts of Montana during the morninghours. Strong winds produced subzero wind-chill readings and poorvisibility.   Before moving out by midday, the storm system also covered roadswith ice and left 2 inches of wind-whipped snow in much of Utah. Arash of accidents, including a fatal car-train collision, wasblamed on the storm there.   Snow and gusty winds were also reported as far east as thecentral Plains. A high wind warning was posted in the mountains ofNew Mexico, and wind advisories were posted in some Texas mountainpasses and the mountains of Southern California.   An advisory for snow was posted for the northern and centralmountains and the northeastern plains of Colorado, and a winterstorm watch was been posted through Tuesday morning fornorthwestern Kansas.   Farther south, the front created some fears of severethunderstorms and possible tornadoes in parts of southeasternKansas, Oklahoma and west-central Texas.   In northern and central Minnesota, the precipitation took theform of a mixture of rain, freezing drizzle and snow, while showersand thunderstorms were numerous across southern Wisconsin, northernand central Illinois, and northeastern Missouri, and fromsouthwestern Iowa to north-central Texas.   Heavier rainfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 1 p.m.EST included 0.89 inch at Rockford, Ill.; 0.85 inch at Peoria,Ill.; 0.56 inch at Madison, Wis.; 0.48 inch at Dubuque, Iowa, andMoline, Ill., and 0.47 inch at Cedar Rapids, Iowa.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 18degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 92 degrees at McAllen, Texas.The early morning low for the nation was zero at Yellowstone Park.   The forecast for Tuesday called for showers and thunderstorms inthe southern and central Plains and the Mississippi Valley to theGreat Lakes, with snow in parts of northern Minnesota and UpperMichigan. Rain showers, with snow in the higher elevations, alsowere forecast across the Pacific Northwest into the northernRockies.   Temperatures in the 30s and 40s were forecast from the northernand central Rockies through the northern and central Plains toUpper Michigan, and across northern New England; in the 70s inSouthern California and southern Arizona, and from the Rio GrandeValley of Texas to the southern and mid-Atlantic Coast states; inthe 80s in south-central Texas and across the Florida Peninsula,and in the 50s and 60s in most of the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>